ce:section.ce:para:
Weng and Lin's group have used positively charged N,S co-doped CDs (P-CDs) for ratiometric sensing of DNA, where they played roles both of a nano-quencher and a reference signal. They were synthesized with an easy two-step procedure by pyrolysis from citric acid and L-glutathione (
                     Fig. 2a
                     ). Obtained CDs possessed an amino-rich surface and demonstrated a continuous stability of fluorescence, satisfactory quantum yield and strong photobleaching resistance. P-CDs have shown themselves as a powerful quencher towards fluorophore-modified DNA with their inherent luminescence preserved which makes them a promising tool for the detection of DNA by hybridization with complementary DNA sequence. The comparison of P-CDs with citric acid CDs have shown that quenching efficiency of P-CDs towards carboxyfluorescein-labeled ssDNA is much higher than that of citric acid CDs (76 % vs. 23 %). Also, P-CDs have exhibited twice as greater quantum yield (12.7 % vs. 6.96 %) compared to citric acid CDs which are prepared by direct pyrolysis strategy without any doping or passivation of polyene polyamine [44].
